No one can fail to he struck by the multitude of adjtuations with which the dialogue in Plautus and Terence is interlarded, and which are, for the most part, mere expletives, desti· tute of any particular emphasis, corresponding to the ‘Gad‚' ‘Bedad,' ‘Faith,' ‘By Jove,’ and a host of others, with which many of our dramatists were wont to season the discourse of their characters.

The words of this kind which appear to have been most in favour with the Romans were, as might be anticipated, appcals to their popular deities, the Great Twin Brethren aud Hercules, expressed by Pol, Edepol, Mecastor, Ecastor, Hercle, dec.

Pol is manifestly an abbreviation of Pollux, and is used either as an independens ejaculation or in connection with verbs and such adverbs as certe, sanc, profecto. The combination Per pol, found in Hec. 1. i. 1, Per pol quam paucos repertas meretricibus lldcks evenire matoes, Sura, is so strange that commentatore have sought to explain it by mas, conjoining the per with quam.

Edepol has been held to be a contractiori for per aedem Pollucis, and hence is sometimes printed aedepol, but it is probably merely another form of Epol, which is found occasionally in the MSS. of Plautus. Pol and Edepol in the extant Latin writers are freely used by men and women alilre.

Mecastor, we cannot doubt, stands for mc, Castor, iuoa, or me Castor suaet, ‘so help me, Castor,' as Meherculcs or Mehercule stand for me, Hercules, aava, or rae Hercules suaet, and Medeicsfidius for nte, Dius Fideles, aava, or me Dius didius suaet, ‘so help me, God of Truth!

Ecastor, although explained like Edepol to be a contractiori for per aedem Castores, seems to be simply the name Castor with the ejaculatory particle e prefixed, as in Equirine (Paul. Diac. p. 81, ed. Mun), Esioso (Charis p. 183, ed. Puta), and Epol, noticed above.
